{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_dungenesscrab_ver01/data/sn84020662/00414185435/1957112901/0331.xml":{"full_text":"Z\u00a3 NOME NUGGET\nOLDEST NEWSPAPER IN ALASKA\u2014LIZL3ER ASSOCIATED PRESS\nVOL. LIX No. 142 NOME, ALASKA, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 29, 1957 Per Copy\u201415#\nKefauver Finds Status of U.S.\nMissiles Program Worse Than\nHe Thought After Testimony\nWASHINGTON. U5V-Sen. Ke\nfauver (D-Tenn) said today three\ndays of testimony on the status\nof the U. S. missiles program\nshows the situation \u201cis worse than\nI thought it was.\u201d\nKefauver, a member of the Sen\nate Preparedness Subcommittee\nconducting the missiles-satellite\nprobe, said in an interview the\ntestimony by defense officials, in\ntelligence specialists and scien\ntists added up to \u201cshocking evi\ndence of how the country has got\nten behind\u201d Russia in certain\nscientific-military fields.\nMore Money for Missiles\nBut the Tennessean said, \u201cThe\npicture is not hopeless,\u201d adding:\n\u201cWe\u2019ve got to give more money\nand attention to missiles, satel\nlites and scientific development\nand education. We can catch up\nand get ahead if wp only put our\nwill to it.\u201d\nOther subcommittee members\nwho sat in on a closed-door intel\nligence briefing Wednesday said\nafterward they heard a \u201csad and\nshocking\u201d story on Russian mili\ntary-scientific progress. The brief\ning was given by Allen Dulles,\nchief of the Central Intelligence\nAgency.\nThese senators, too, decline to\nsay just what they learned from\nthe CIA chief. But it was reported\nlast night tha^ the subcommittee\nwas told Russia now has a few\nsubmarines, possibly four, capa\nble of firing a missile with a nu\nclear warhead up to 700-900 miles.\nOther vessels in Russia\u2019s sub\nfleet, estimated at about 450 boats,\nwere reported being readied for\nsuch missile equipment.\nU.S. East Coast Jeapordized\nOne informant said the report\ned Soviet sub-missile capability\n\u201cmeans they are practically in a\nposition to wipe out any major\ncity on the eastern seaboard.\u201d\nHe did not say, however, that\nany of the Russian subs now are\nstationed within missile range of\nthe east coast.\nThe CIA was quoted by one\n(Continued on Page Four)\nAt Least 180 Killed in Uprising\nIn Spanish Colony of Ifni; King of\nMorocco Confers During U.S. Tour\nRABAT, Morocco, (1P>\u2014Spanish\nbombers have killed at least 1301\npersons in the rebellious colony of\nIfni, the newspaper A1 Alam said!\ntoday. Spanish forces launched\nattacks by land and sea yesterday\nin their effort to crush the upris\ning, it added.\nThe paper, organ of the Moroc\ncan lstiqlal (independence) Party,\nsaid 50 persons were killed by\nbombs in the village of Fouar and\n130 in Uidi Hamed Larouss.\nPlanes and ships bombarded\nthe Moroccan village of Chira,\nnorth of the Ifni enclave yester\nday and the villages of Oum Ifis\nsin and Shouikhat, in the south-\neast corner of the enclave, were i\nbombed and machinegunned, and\ncaused \u201cmany casualties,\u201d by A11\nAlam\u2019s account.\nThe paper carried a map of the!\nIfni enclave showing the rebels in\ncontrol of three-quarters of the\narea after five days of fighting;\nall of it except a coastal strip and\na half circle around Sidi Ifni.\nMoroccan officials spoke of re\nvolts in Ifni, implying uprisings\nby the Berber tribesmen who live\nin the 741-square-mile enclave.\nThe Spanish said the fighting\narose from raids by the Moroccan\nLiberation Army, an irregular\nforce not directly controlled by\nRabat.\nWILLIAMSBURG, Va\u201e UP>\u2014\nKing Mohammed V of Morocco\nturned his attention today from\nan American sightseeing tour to\nan irregular war back home over\nthe Spanish colony of Ifni.\nThe King was to confer on the\nfighting with the chief aide of his\nson, who has been running the\nMoroccan government since Mo\nhammed flew to Washington on\nSunday. The aide, Col. Moulay\nHafid, flew in yesterday from\nRabat.\nThe King and his party were\nscheduled to leave this restored\ncolonial capital of Virgina at 8\na.m. for a flight to Dallas. His 16\nday tour of the United States will\ninclude later stops at Los Angeles,\nSan Francisco, Omaha and New\nYork City.\nMohammed flew here on a spe\ncial Air Force Constellation after\nVice President Nixon bade him a\nwarm farewell in Washington.\nAides said the 48-year-old mon\narch was immensely pleased with\nresults of his talks with Secretary\nof State Dulles.\nHafid, aide to Crown Prince\nMoulay Hassan, arived later to\nbrief the King on fighting in the\ntiny Spanish colony of Ifni facing\nthe Atlantic and surrounded by\nMorocco on three sides.\nTHE GREAT LOVE STORY JaneWyman SUNDAY and MONDAY\nBY THE AUTHOR OF ISS AT NOMERAMA\n\u201cTHE ROBE\u201d |.ro-S5Sa 1st Show at 7:15 2nd Show 9:15\ni\nDECISION ON\nFREIGHT RATES\nMAY COME SOON\nWASHINGTON, UP>\u2014Alaskans\nmay learn today what, i{ any.\nfreight rate increase may be put\ninto effect Monday.\nBecause today the final working\nday of the Federal Maritime\nBoard before Monday, it is the\npractical deadline for action by\nthe board to forestall the 15 per\ncent boost asked by the Alaska\nSteamship Co. and Coastwise\nLines.\nWhile J^ie board may find the\nproposed increase reasonable and\npermit it to go into effect as is\nscheduled, agency sources said in\nview of protests received it is\nlikely the board will follow one\nof several alternate courses.\nThese include suspending all or\npart of the requested increase for\nperiods up to four months to per\nmit an investigation and hearing,*\nor permitting all or part of the\nincrease to become effective sub\nject to refund if later disallowed.\nPresident of Tunisia\nAnnoucement Throws\nRebels Into Confusion\nTUNIS, Tunisia, \u2014President\nHabib Bourguiba claims the Al\ngerian National Liberation Front\n(FLN) has made a major -revision\nin policy in the Algerian rebellion\nand no longer is insisting upon\nindependence before negotiating\nwith France.\nThe statement threw FLN head\nquarters here into confusion.\nIn making a recording for his\nweekly broadcast in Arabic to the\nTunisian people last night, Bour\nguiba said: \u201cThe FLN leaders\nhave abandoned the demand for\na prior grant of inlependence in\nresponse to our appeal.\u201d\nThe Tunisian ministry of speech\nheld back the page continuing the\nstatement. But the ministry is\nsued it later in a slightly differ\nent form, with the meaning un\nchanged. When the tape recording\nwas finally made in Arabic the\noriginal statement remained.\nFLN sources, after hours of dis\ncussion, said today Bourguiba pos\nsibly had made \u201ca slip of the\ntongue.\u201d They did not deny his\nstatement, however.\nCG Cutter Storis Nears\nLast Lap in Voyage\nAround North America\nSAN FRANCISCO, UP>\u2014T h e\nCoast Guard cutter Storis has ar\nrived enroute to Seattle\u2014the last\nleg in the circumnavigation of\nNorth America by way of the\narctic.\nThe vessel lef\u00a3 Seattle last July\n1 to seek a deep water channel\nthru the arctic. The skipper is\nCmdr. H. L. Wood of Trenton,\nN.J. The Storis\u2019 home port is Ko\ndiak, Alaska.\nThe route was across the top of\nPrince of Wales Strait, then re\nturn via the Panama Canal.\nEisenhower Continues to Make\nRapid Recovery From Stroke;\nMay Attend NATO Meeting Dec. 16\n-4\nFrance to Accept\nMoroccan Help\nIn Algerian Crisis\nPARIS (\u00a3>\u2014France today reject\ned the mediation offer of Moroc\nco and Tunisia but agreed to ac\ncept their help in seeking a cease\nfire to end the three-year nation\nalist rebellion in Algeria.\nThe French decision was an\nnounced by Premier Felix Gail\nlard in the National Assembly as\nhe made a final plea for two gov\nernment bills which are intended\nto give Algeria at least partial\nhome rule once peace has been\nrestored there.\nThe bills\u2014one setting up a fed\neral form of government for the\nterritory\u2019s home affairs and the\nother ruling on how elections\nshould be organized to give fair\nrepresentation for both Moslems\nand Europeans\u2014were both made\nissues of confidence in the three\nweek-old Gaillard government.\nGaillard told the deputies that\nhe well understood the uneasiness\nof the former French protector\nates of Morocco and Tunisia.\n\u201cBut,\u201d he added, \u201cthe basic\npolicies of France cannot be\nchanged. We will never agree to\nconsider the million Frenchmen\nof European origin as foreigners j\nin their native territory where\nthey must keep their rights.\u201d\nGaillard said nothing was pos\nsible without a cease-fire. And\nthere is no need for a conference\nfor that, he said.\nBritish Opinion Divided Over\nU.S. Bombers Carring H-Bombs\n\nOn Training Flights Over Britain\nLONDON, Iff)\u2014While Laborites\ncontinued to express misgivings\nabout U.S. bombers making train\ning flights from Britain with H\nbombs aboard, the British press\nrallied to the Conservative gov\nernment\u2019s stand today.\nThe most widely read paper in\nthe country. The Daily Mirror,\nsaid today East-West tensions\nfully justify arming the bombers\nwith nuclear weapons. The inde\npendent newspaper usually sup\nports the Labor Party.\nThe carrying of bombs was re\nvealed in the House of Commons\nWednesday when Foreign Secre\ntary Selwyn Lloyd said he \u201cshould\nthink they do. Prime Minister\nMacMillan stepped in yesterday\nto allay some of the tension that\nwas raised.\nMacMillan said U.S. authorities\nhave taken elaborate precautions\nto prevent a nuclear blast should\na bomb-carrying plane crash. He\nexplained that the planes carry\nbombs in separate parts that have\nto be expertly assembled before\na nuclear explosion is possible.\nSome Labor groups reacted to\nthe news with resolutions oppos\ning the practice of flying H-bombs\naround over Englishmen\u2019s heads.\nThe Laborite Daily Herald\nquoted some Britons living near\nU.S. bases as expressing fear of\nbeing killed in a nuclear blast.\nWASHINGTON, (*)\u2014President\nEisenhower set out by automobile\ntoday for a weekend or more at\nhis Pennsylvania farm in a strik\ning new demonstration of speedy\nrecovery from his mild stroke.\nThe Chief Executive, piling the\nmove on top of yesterday\u2019s burst\nof activity which included sur\nprise attendance at a Thanksgiv\ning church service, went with full\napproval from his doctors, the\nWhite House said.\nA Cabinet meeting is scheduled\nMonday. And on Tuesday, con\ngressional leaders of both parties\nare coming to the White House\nfor a briefing on military and de\nfense matters and the legislative\nprogram for the new congression\nal session.\nIf the President decides to stay\non at his farm for awhile, he will\nconduct a limited amount of gov\nernment business from the farm\nheadquarters. He convalesced at\nthe farm from his 1955 heart at\ntack and his 1956- intestinal ill\nness.\nAny forecast last Tuesday that\nEisenhower would be traveling to\nGettysburg today would have\nbeen roundly challenged. It was\nthen, three days ago, that his doc\ntors announced he had suffered a\nblockage of a brain artery branch.\nSlight stroke is the common term\nfor that kind of seizure.\nThere were these other encour\naging developments:\n1. The White House physician,\nMaj. Gen. Howard M. Snyder, put\nout another medical bulletin re\nporting the President was contin\nuing to make excellent recovery\n{Continued on Page Two)","height":"18087","width":"13197"}}
